TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding Shifting Power Relations within and across Organizations: A Critical Genre Analysis
AU  - Levina, Natalia
AU  - Orlikowski, Wanda J.
Y1  - 2009/08/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.43669902
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.43669902
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 672
EP  - 703
VL  - 52
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on an in-depth qualitative study of a consulting project, we examine how conditions of novelty and ambiguity on interorganizational engagements produce inconsistent norms and expectations for guiding project interaction. Clients and consultants attempt to resolve the resulting discursive tensions while also increasing their organization's influence on the project. As diverse institutional contexts offer multiple legitimate ways of practicing, agents draw on such alternatives to renegotiate power relations. We develop a theoretical framework and empirical approach for understanding how discursive resources from diverse institutional contexts can be used to transform power relations within and between organizations.
AB  - Drawing on an in-depth qualitative study of a consulting project, we examine how conditions of novelty and ambiguity on interorganizational engagements produce inconsistent norms and expectations for guiding project interaction. Clients and consultants attempt to resolve the resulting discursive tensions while also increasing their organization's influence on the project. As diverse institutional contexts offer multiple legitimate ways of practicing, agents draw on such alternatives to renegotiate power relations. We develop a theoretical framework and empirical approach for understanding how discursive resources from diverse institutional contexts can be used to transform power relations within and between organizations.
